  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The \"Rigor and Transparency Index\" represents a significant advancement in evaluating biological and medical science methodologies, having garnered 100 citations since its initial preprint on bioRxiv. This contribution has sparked extensive scholarly interest, with the article subsequently passing peer review and being formally published with 84 additional citations.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The \"Rigor and Transparency Index,\" authored by a multidisciplinary team including Joseph Menke and Maryann E. Martone, has emerged as a pivotal metric for assessing quality in biological and medical research methodologies. Since its initial release on bioRxiv, this work has accumulated 100 citations, signaling its relevance and influence within the academic community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The engagement surrounding the work is underscored by its successful transition from preprint to formal publication, with the final version receiving 84 additional citations. This trajectory reflects the article's acceptance and incorporation into ongoing discussions within the field, as well as its role in shaping research practices in the life sciences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The geographical diversity of the research landscape is noteworthy, with key contributions from institutions in the United States and the United Kingdom, among others. The robust citation count, including references from prestigious venues such as Nature and mAbs, exemplifies the growing recognition of the need for rigorous and transparent methodologies in experimental design.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the work has demonstrated significant downstream reuse, evident from its proven impact on subsequent research initiatives, with a count of 101 reuses. This further highlights the article's role in facilitating advancements across related studies, thereby enhancing the overall quality and integrity of scientific inquiry.</p>",
